</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[828,919,951,977]" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="144" pageNumber="145" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="144.[189,324,1018,1044]" box="[189,324,1018,1044]" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,1018,1044]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,1018,1044]" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="144.[189,1399,1065,1127]" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">
The specific epithet is from the Latin ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2018" box="[663,777,1065,1091]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perlobata">
<emphasis box="[663,777,1065,1091]" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">perlobata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, meaning ‘exceedingly lobed’ and referring to the unusually many-lobed surstylus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
